I remember learning about how to treat phobias for my psych degree. It was really interesting. My class watched a video of a woman who went to a psychiatric professional and was able to cope with her fear of snakes after working with him for one 24-hour period. She went from looking at a picture of a snake to being able to hold one! Yes, exposure is able to help but it has to be in EXTREMELY small doses. Also, the client must be willing to treat their fear in order to have it treated, not just shown their fear out of the blue. It's a very touchy thing. Exposing someone to his/her fear too quickly and directly can cause the phobia to become more potent rather than less.
(Edit: btw this is  in reference to fears that you  have such as guns firing around you, being put into situations where you are taken advantage of, etc. my apologies)
(Edit… again: yes you - and hunting dogs - can get used to guns firing through exposure but I was just trying to give an example of danger holy moly…)
